## TCFD — Governance

{% if tcfd_routing == 'cross_reference' %}
> **Cross-reference**: The Company's governance of climate-related risks and
> opportunities is disclosed in full under CSRD ESRS 2 GOV-1 (Board oversight)
> and GOV-3 (Management roles). This section satisfies TCFD Governance
> Recommendations (a) and (b) by reference to those disclosures.
{% else %}
### (a) Board Oversight

The Board of Directors is responsible for oversight of climate-related risks
and opportunities. The {{ board_committee_name | default("Audit and Sustainability Committee") }}
reviews climate-related matters at least quarterly and reports findings to
the full Board.

### (b) Management's Role

The Chief Sustainability Officer (CSO) leads the Company's climate strategy
and reports directly to the CEO. Climate risk and opportunity assessment is
integrated into the annual strategic planning cycle.
{% endif %}

{% elif section == 'strategy' %}
## TCFD — Strategy

{% if tcfd_routing == 'cross_reference' %}
> **Cross-reference**: The Company's climate-related strategy, including
> scenario analysis and resilience assessment, is disclosed under CSRD ESRS
> E1-1 (transition plan) and ESRS 2 SBM-3 (material impacts, risks,
> opportunities). This section satisfies TCFD Strategy Recommendations
> (a), (b), and (c) by reference.
{% else %}
### (a) Climate-Related Risks and Opportunities

Identified over the short (< 3 years), medium (3–10 years), and long
(> 10 years) term:

**Transition risks**: Policy and legal (carbon pricing, CBAM), technology
(stranded assets), market (demand shift), reputational (ESG ratings).

**Physical risks**: Acute (extreme weather events), chronic (sea-level rise,
chronic heat stress on operations).

**Opportunities**: Energy efficiency, renewable energy adoption, green
product/service development.

### (b) Impact on Strategy and Financial Planning

Climate-related scenarios assessed: IEA Net Zero 2050 (1.5°C), IEA
Stated Policies (2.5–3°C). Material financial impacts are incorporated into
the {{ planning_horizon | default("5-year") }} financial plan and disclosed
in the ESRS 2 SBM-3 impact table.

### (c) Resilience of Strategy

Under both scenarios, the Company's core business model is assessed as
resilient, subject to continued execution of the transition plan. The
principal residual risk is Scope 3 (category 11 use-of-sold-products)
emissions trajectory.
{% endif %}

{% elif section == 'risk_management' %}
## TCFD — Risk Management

{% if tcfd_routing == 'cross_reference' %}
> **Cross-reference**: The Company's ESG risk identification, assessment,
> and management processes are disclosed under CSRD ESRS 2 IRO-1 and
> IRO-2. This section satisfies TCFD Risk Management Recommendations
> (a), (b), and (c) by reference.
{% else %}
### (a) Risk Identification and Assessment

Climate-related risks are identified through a structured double-materiality
assessment conducted {{ risk_assessment_cadence | default("bi-annually") }}.
Physical risk exposure is mapped using {{ climate_data_provider | default("third-party climate analytics") }}
under RCP 2.6 and RCP 4.5 scenarios.

### (b) Risk Management Processes

Identified material climate risks are assigned owners, tracked in the
enterprise risk register, and reviewed by the {{ risk_committee_name | default("Risk Committee") }}.
Mitigation actions are included in departmental KPIs.

### (c) Integration into Overall Risk Management

Climate risk is integrated into the Company's ERM framework alongside
financial, operational, and cyber risks. The ERM framework is reviewed
annually by the Board.
{% endif %}

